[The CFIA circulated the following instructions and advisories on 5 Apr 2013:

Notice to Industry -- Anthrax Program Changes:
The Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) is reminding livestock producers and other stakeholders that the anthrax program changed on 1 Apr 2013:
http://inspection.gc.ca/eng/1365172195510/1365172269260

Cleaning and Disinfection of Anthrax-Contaminated Sites and Materials:
http://inspection.gc.ca/eng/1363954818609/1363954874392

Disposal of Anthrax Carcasses and Contaminated Materials:
http://inspection.gc.ca/eng/1363802986241/1363803524106

The Canadian government initiated subsidy payments of some CAD 500 [USD 490] each in the early 1960s to farmers reporting outbreaks of livestock anthrax. And they also provided some 3 years of herd vaccinations. This proactive activity resulted in the immediate public appreciation of anthrax across the prairies where it had been lurking in plain sight since the 1920s. It has been very successful and one of the benefits has been the emergence of a uniform response. But latterly CFIA found that the ranchers were not bothering to vaccinate their herds annually but instead were waiting until there was an outbreak and then use the federal funding. This did little to reduce the incidence.

I hold the Canadian federal and provincial veterinary services in high regard but I must admit to holding my breath to see how the coming anthrax seasons will turn out. Frankly there is an enzootic risk across the prairies, especially in Manitoba and Saskatchewan, and outbreaks are best prevented by aggressively advising the ranchers to vaccinate their stock each spring, especially on ranches which have had recent outbreaks or whose neighbours were affected. Charlie Stoltenow has ably demonstrated the benefits of this by his hard extension work in North Dakota in the last few years. Outbreaks there are now few and limited to the non-vaccinators. - Mod.MHJ]
